---
scope: src/service/install/buildInstallConfig/
intent: >
  Generate the exact MCP config JSON block and the `aide_init` command
  string the landing page's install block renders, targeting Claude Code
  only in v1. The content must be correct for Claude Code's `.mcp.json`
  shape, accompanied by the three-step paste-restart-`aide_init`
  sequence, surfaced with a troubleshooting callout for the known
  friction modes, and updated only when the `aidemd-mcp` interface
  itself changes. The snippet must use the `@latest` dist-tag to
  guarantee `npx` always fetches the newest published version rather
  than serving a stale cache. This submodule owns the literal text that
  lands on the visitor's screen and flows into their `.mcp.json`; any
  ambiguity here kills conversion.
outcomes:
  desired:
    - The JSON block rendered on the landing is valid JSON, directly pasteable into a `.mcp.json` file, and uses the exact `mcpServers.aide.command` + `mcpServers.aide.args` shape Claude Code's MCP loader expects.
    - The args array in the rendered JSON contains `@aidemd-mcp/server@latest` — the `@latest` dist-tag ensures `npx` bypasses any locally cached version and fetches the newest published release on every invocation.
    - The command sequence shown to the visitor is complete and explicit: (1) paste the config into `.mcp.json`, (2) restart Claude Code so the new MCP server is loaded, (3) call `aide_init` from the tool palette. No step is elided or collapsed.
    - A visitor who follows the steps exactly, with `npx` available on PATH, reaches a working AIDE installation in under two minutes without needing external documentation.
    - Content updates only when `aidemd-mcp` publishes a breaking change to its MCP config shape or its `aide_init` tool interface. No drift between what the landing says and what the MCP server expects.
    - The install content is a typed constant (discriminated union keyed by host framework) so v1's Claude Code variant is the only shipped case but multi-host expansion is a type change, not a rewrite.
  undesired:
    - Multi-framework tab mechanics in v1. The install block is a single code block and a single command sequence, not a tabbed interface. Tabs imply multi-framework support the v1 scope does not claim.
    - Semver version pinning in the snippet (`npx @aidemd-mcp/server@0.2.0`, `@^1.2.3`). Semver pins rot the moment the next version ships and nobody updates the landing. The `@latest` dist-tag is not version pinning — it is a freshness guarantee that forces `npx` to fetch the newest published version.
    - Bare package name without the `@latest` dist-tag (`npx @aidemd-mcp/server` with no tag). `npx` may serve a locally cached copy when no dist-tag is specified, which means a visitor silently gets an old version with no visible error. The `@latest` tag is required to prevent stale-cache surprises.
    - Hidden prerequisites. If the flow assumes Node 18+, that is stated visibly in the troubleshooting callout. If it assumes `npx` on PATH, that is stated. "It just works" is not a spec outcome; "it works and visitors know exactly why it might not" is.
    - Elided restart step. Claude Code must be restarted after `.mcp.json` changes so it picks up the new MCP server; omitting the restart from the displayed sequence makes `aide_init` invisible from the tool palette and the install silently fails with no visible error.
    - Copy that implies `aide_init` is the "install" step and the JSON paste is optional. Both matter, and the order matters: the paste wires the MCP server, the restart loads it, the `aide_init` call bootstraps the methodology into the project.
    - Runtime fetch of the install content. The config is a build-time constant; the landing server-renders the HTML.
    - Hardcoded dollar figures, hero copy, or landing-level decisions in this module. The install-content module owns the install block's literal config and commands only. Hero copy lives in the landing spec's Good Examples; cost-strip numbers live in the landing spec's Good Examples. Cross-contamination violates scope.
    - Auto-detect marketing in v1 copy. `aide_init` does auto-detect the framework (reading the source: the `framework` input is an optional discriminated union), but v1 ships Claude Code only. Bragging about auto-detection promises multi-framework support v1 does not deliver.
---

## Context

The install block is the landing's single CTA and literally the hero's
visual. Any ambiguity in its content — a typo in the JSON, a missing
comma, a wrong key name, a skipped step — kills conversion and the
visitor assumes AIDE is broken rather than that the documentation is
wrong. This submodule exists so that the literal text visitors copy
and paste is generated from a typed contract, not hand-authored in
JSX, so drift between "what the landing says" and "what the MCP
server expects" is structurally impossible.

The parent context (from the landing spec) is that the install block
IS the hero visual and is the single conversion path. This submodule
narrows to the specific correctness guarantee for the text inside
that block.

## Strategy

**Static typed fixture, built at compile time.** The install content
is a module-level constant of type `InstallConfig`, which in v1 is a
discriminated union with exactly one variant: `{ framework: "claude",
mcpConfig: { mcpServers: { aide: { command: "npx", args:
["@aidemd-mcp/server@latest"] } } }, commandSequence: [...] }`. The union shape
means adding Cursor, Windsurf, or Copilot later is a type addition,
not a rewrite — but v1 ships one variant.

**JSON is serialized from the typed object, never hand-typed.** The
code block rendered in the install UI comes from `JSON.stringify` on
the typed `mcpConfig` field with two-space indent. This guarantees
valid JSON, guarantees consistent formatting, and makes it impossible
to ship a trailing-comma syntax error.

**Command sequence is explicit and three-step.** The exported
`commandSequence` array contains three entries: (1) "Paste this into
your project's `.mcp.json`" with the JSON block, (2) "Restart Claude
Code so it loads the new MCP server" with no code, (3) "Call
`aide_init` from the tool palette" with the command name as inline
code. The landing renders each step with its number and its content.
The restart step is not collapsed, not skipped, and not described as
optional — Claude Code's `.mcp.json` reload behavior requires the
restart and the spec names it explicitly.

**Friction modes are surfaced, not hidden.** A troubleshooting callout
lives beside the install block and names the known friction modes:
`npx` not on PATH (install Node or restart terminal), Node version
too old (18+ required), shell initialization issue under nvm or
Homebrew (PATH not inherited into Claude Code's shell), quit-vs-close
distinction on macOS (use Cmd+Q, not red-dot). Each mode has a
one-line symptom and a one-line fix. Per the architect's decision,
the troubleshooting content is static JSX inside the landing's
`TroubleshootingCallout/` component rather than generated here — this
module owns the install config and sequence; the callout's prose lives
adjacent in the landing's component tree. This spec names the callout
as a required sibling so the landing cannot ship the install block
alone.

**`@latest` dist-tag, not semver pins or bare names.** The args array
uses `@aidemd-mcp/server@latest` — the explicit `@latest` dist-tag,
not a semver pin and not the bare package name. These are three
distinct behaviors in `npx`: a semver pin (`@0.2.0`, `@^1.2.3`) rots
the moment the next version ships and nobody updates the landing; a
bare package name (no tag at all) lets `npx` serve a locally cached
copy from its internal store without checking the registry, which
means a visitor who ran an older version once silently gets that old
version forever with no visible error; the `@latest` dist-tag forces
`npx` to resolve against the registry's `latest` tag on every
invocation, guaranteeing the newest published release. The `@latest`
tag is not version pinning — it is a freshness guarantee. When a
breaking change lands in `aidemd-mcp`, this module's fixture updates
(and the landing rebuilds), which is the one allowed trigger for
updating this file.

**Precondition: `aidemd-mcp` is published to npm at launch.** The
`npx @aidemd-mcp/server@latest` resolution requires the package to
exist on the public npm registry. At the time of writing this spec,
the package is not yet published (`npm view @aidemd-mcp/server`
returns 404); this is a
pre-launch coordination gate, not a code fix, and is surfaced here
so the implementor does not ship the site expecting the install to
work before publishing happens. If this changes, this paragraph
stays as historical context but stops being a precondition.

**Claude Code only. No auto-detect bragging.** v1 ships one framework
variant. The copy says "works with Claude Code" once, plainly, and
does not promise "also works with..." anything. The fact that
`aide_init` internally auto-detects the host is an implementation
detail of the MCP server, not a selling point of the landing — bragging
about it would imply multi-framework support that has not been tested.
When the other frameworks are tested and the landing expands to
multi-host, this spec gets a revision and the discriminated union
grows.

**Content updates only on interface changes.** The only reason to
touch this file is that `aidemd-mcp` has changed its MCP config shape
or its `aide_init` interface. Drift between what visitors paste and
what the server expects is the failure mode this submodule prevents;
the typed static fixture is the discipline. Any other change — a new
hero variant, a different troubleshooting line, a rewording of the
restart step — does not belong here.

## Good examples

**The typed fixture (structure, not code):**

An `InstallConfig` value whose `framework` is `"claude"`, whose
`mcpConfig` is the two-line `mcpServers.aide` object pointing at
`npx @aidemd-mcp/server@latest`, and whose `commandSequence` is a three-step array
naming paste / restart / `aide_init`.

**What the landing renders, verbatim:**

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "aide": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["@aidemd-mcp/server@latest"]
    }
  }
}
```

Below the code block, three numbered steps:

1. Paste this into your project's `.mcp.json`.
2. Restart Claude Code so it loads the new MCP server.
3. Call `aide_init` from the tool palette.

Beside the block, a troubleshooting callout reading:

> **Install not appearing?** `npx` not on PATH: install Node or restart
> terminal. Node too old: upgrade to 18+. `aide_init` not in the tool
> palette: make sure you fully quit Claude Code (Cmd+Q on macOS), then
> reopen. nvm/Homebrew path issue: start Claude Code from a shell
> where `which npx` resolves.

A visitor with Node 20 and a project already open in Claude Code
copies the JSON, pastes it into `.mcp.json`, Cmd+Q's Claude Code,
reopens, sees `aide_init` in the tool palette, calls it, and sees
`.aide/` appear in their project with the canonical hub inside. Total
elapsed time: about ninety seconds.

## Bad examples

The install block renders a tabbed interface with four tabs — Claude
Code / Cursor / Windsurf / Copilot — three of which show the same
`npx @aidemd-mcp/server@latest` config with a different key name and none of which
have been tested with AIDE end-to-end. A visitor on Cursor pastes
the Cursor snippet and nothing happens; they close the tab and don't
come back.

The JSON block is a string literal in JSX with a hand-typed trailing
comma that isn't valid JSON. Visitors paste it into `.mcp.json` and
Claude Code fails to parse the config file entirely, breaking their
existing MCP servers. A bug report lands three days later.

The sequence omits the restart step. Visitors paste the config, open
the tool palette, don't see `aide_init`, assume it's broken, and
close the tab. A bug report reads "install instructions don't work."
The fix is one line of copy, but the conversion has already been
lost.

The snippet pins `npx @aidemd-mcp/server@0.2.0`. When 0.3 ships with
a bug-fix, visitors still get the buggy version; when 1.0 ships with
a breaking change, visitors silently get the old version and their
install works differently from what the docs describe.

The args array uses `@aidemd-mcp/server` with no dist-tag. A visitor
who ran `npx @aidemd-mcp/server` once three months ago has version
0.1.0 sitting in their local `npx` cache. Today the landing tells
them to paste the same snippet. `npx` sees the cached copy, skips the
registry check, and serves the stale version. The visitor gets a
broken or outdated install with zero indication anything went wrong —
no error, no warning, no version mismatch message. The `@latest` tag
would have forced a registry lookup and pulled the current release.

The troubleshooting callout says "if it doesn't work, try again" with
no specific diagnoses. A visitor on nvm with an old default Node
version hits the Node-too-old failure, reads the useless callout,
gives up.

A contributor adds auto-detect marketing copy: "AIDE automatically
detects Claude Code, Cursor, Windsurf, and Copilot!" — which is
technically true of `aide_init`'s implementation but implies v1 has
been tested on all four, which it hasn't. The spec's
`outcomes.undesired` catches this on review.
